 data-bs-target=3D"#nav_scrollspy"><div id=3D"pgtype-ref"><div class=3D"obj=
ect_ref"><span id=3D"mw_533ed864-bcf6-497a-9428-0c7f6dc8b9e8" class=3D"anch=
or_target"></span><h1 class=3D"r2023b notranslate" itemprop=3D"title">ortho=
sliceViewer</h1><div class=3D"doc_topic_desc"><div class=3D"purpose_contain=
er"><p itemprop=3D"purpose" class=3D"add_margin_0">Browse orthogonal slices=
 in grayscale or RGB volume</p><p class=3D"add_margin_0 add_clear_left"><em=
>Since R2019b</em></p><div class=3D"switch mwToggle0"><a id=3D"expandAllPag=
e">expand all in page</a></div></div></div><div class=3D"refsummary" itempr=
op=3D"content"><h2 id=3D"d126e246058">Description</h2>
    <div class=3D"shortsummary"><p>An <code class=3D"object">orthosliceView=
er</code> object displays volumetric image data by
      presenting three orthogonal views of the volume along the <em class=
=3D"varname">x</em>,
        <em class=3D"varname">y</em>, and <em class=3D"varname">z</em> dime=
nsions.</p></div>
    <p>Use <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> to look at indivi=
dual slices in a volume. The
        <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> opens, displaying th=
e center slice in each dimension. Each
      view of the image stack includes a crosshair that you can use to view=
 the different slices of
      the image stack. The crosshairs are linked so that if you move one, t=
he crosshairs in the
      related views also move.</p>
    <div class=3D"informalfigure"><div id=3D"d126e246079" class=3D"mediaobj=
ect"><p><img src=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/images/re=
f/orthoslice_viewer_ov.png" height=3D"527" width=3D"497"></p></div></div>
    <p>The <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> object supports p=
roperties, object functions, and
      events that you can use to customize its appearance and functioning. =
The
        <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> object can send noti=
fications when certain events occur,
      such as the crosshair moving. For more information, see <a href=3D"ht=
tps://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/images/ref/orthosliceviewer.htm=
l#mw_0fc5e79e-f690-48d4-86ca-f84932d79e98" class=3D"intrnllnk">Events</a>.<=
/p>
    <div class=3D"alert alert-info"><span class=3D"alert_icon icon-alert-in=
fo-reverse"></span><p class=3D"alert_heading"><strong>Note</strong></p><p>B=
y default, clicking and dragging the mouse in the slices displayed interact=
ively
        changes their brightness and contrast, a technique called
          <em class=3D"firstterm">window/level</em>. Dragging the mouse hor=
izontally from left to right
        changes the contrast. Dragging the mouse vertically up and down cha=
nges the brightness.
        Holding down the <strong class=3D"keycap">Ctrl</strong> key when cl=
icking and dragging the mouse accelerates
        changes. Holding down the <strong class=3D"keycap">Shift</strong> k=
ey while clicking and dragging the mouse
        slows the rate of change. Press these keys before clicking and drag=
ging. To control this
        behavior, use the <a href=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases=
/R2023b/images/ref/orthosliceviewer.html#mw_f5bbdafc-0174-431c-8d3c-3231e53=
526d0" class=3D"intrnllnk"><span class=3D"property">DisplayRangeInteraction=
</span></a>
        property.</p></div>
  </div><div id=3D"mw_bd91ea8d-c1e1-4c50-b719-5573542418ae_div" class=3D"re=
f_sect createobject"><h2 id=3D"mw_bd91ea8d-c1e1-4c50-b719-5573542418ae">Cre=
ation</h2><div id=3D"mw_d4b39e1c-cea4-409b-affb-dcb15dafa622_div" class=3D"=
refsect2 description"><h3 id=3D"mw_d4b39e1c-cea4-409b-affb-dcb15dafa622">De=
scription</h3><div class=3D"description_module"><div class=3D"description_e=
lement"><p class=3D"syntax_example"><a href=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/hel=
p/releases/R2023b/images/ref/orthosliceviewer.html#mw_348384dd-a1b6-440a-9c=
f1-81e8b629ecf5" class=3D"intrnllnk">example</a></p><div class=3D"code_resp=
onsive"><p><span id=3D"d126e246112" itemprop=3D"syntax"><code class=3D"syno=
psis">orthosliceViewer(<a href=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2=
023b/images/ref/orthosliceviewer.html#mw_bba4cfb1-ead1-4fea-a862-19ad4d3254=
2a" class=3D"intrnllnk"><code class=3D"argument">V</code></a>)</code></span=
> displays the volume
            <code class=3D"argument">V</code> in a figure.</p></div></div><=
div class=3D"description_element"><div class=3D"code_responsive"><p><span i=
d=3D"d126e246128" itemprop=3D"syntax"><code class=3D"synopsis">orthosliceVi=
ewer(<span class=3D"argument_placeholder">___</span>,<code class=3D"argumen=
t">Name,Value</code>)</code></span>
          sets <a href=3D"https://ww2.mathworks.cn/help/releases/R2023b/ima=
ges/ref/orthosliceviewer.html#mw_7662ccb4-6cd6-48f7-b5bf-13ec7177dfd1" clas=
s=3D"intrnllnk">properties</a> using
          name-value pair arguments. You can specify multiple name-value pa=
irs. Enclose each
          property name in single quotes.</p><p><span class=3D"example_desc=
"><strong>Example: </strong><code class=3D"literal">orthosliceViewer(V,'Col=
ormap',cmap)</code> creates an
            <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> object and speci=
fies the colormap used to display the
          volume. </span></p></div></div><div class=3D"description_element"=
><div class=3D"code_responsive"><p><span id=3D"d126e246148" itemprop=3D"syn=
tax"><code class=3D"synopsis"><code class=3D"argument">s</code> =3D orthosl=
iceViewer(<span class=3D"argument_placeholder">___</span>)</code></span>
          returns an <code class=3D"object">orthosliceViewer</code> object,=
 <code class=3D"argument">s</code>, with
          properties that can be used to control the visualization of the i=
mages. Use input
          arguments from any of the previous syntaxes.</p></div></div></div=
></div><div class=3D"ref_sect"><h3 id=3D"mw_dbf6bde4-55c1-41ef-9f24-c0c9f14=
